    "intro": "On **22 June** MOFCOM put ten US firms on its export-control list: the US-government-backed rare-earth producers MP Materials and USA Rare Earth, plus Ball Aerospace, Oshkosh Defense, L3Harris Maritime, Red Cat Holdings, Teal Drones, Aveox, IMSAR and Jaia Robotics ([Reuters Jun 22](https://www.reuters.com/world/asia-pacific/china-targets-us-rare-earth-other-firms-with-export-controls-2026-06-22/)). Chinese exporters cannot supply them with dual-use items. Transfers of China-origin dual-use goods to them are blocked worldwide. Existing transactions are suspended pending MOFCOM approval.\n\nThe trigger was **Washington's 8 June expansion of the Pentagon's 1260H list of \"Chinese military companies\"** by 65 firms, including Alibaba, Baidu, BYD, NIO, Unitree, BOE and CXMT. The list now names **188 firms**. From end-June the Defense Department cannot contract with them; from June 2027 the ban extends to indirect procurement. Alibaba, Baidu and NIO announced legal challenges ([CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/06/09/alibaba-baidu-byd-named-on-pentagons-china-military-list-.html), [SCMP](https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3356419/us-adds-alibaba-byd-and-other-chinese-tech-champions-military-company-list)).\n\nWashington is also holding back on some files. On 17 June Reuters reported the US **held off blacklisting DeepSeek and 100+ Chinese firms** US agencies had flagged as security risks, after lobbying from US chip companies ([Reuters Jun 17](https://www.reuters.com/world/china/us-holds-off-blacklisting-chinas-deepseek-more-than-100-firms-deemed-security-2026-06-17/)).\n\nOther moves in the same window:",
