      "title": "Spotlight 2: What's next after the European Council",
      "short": "Spotlight 2: After the European Council",
      "intro": "At the European Council on 18–19 June, leaders asked Ursula von der Leyen to \"continue engaging in constructive dialogue\" with China and to \"develop and eventually complement the toolbox\" on trade defence and industrial policy ([FT](https://www.ft.com/content/e220372c-b20e-418e-9f02-29a5aa269702), Euobserver). Her SOTEU speech in mid-September and the October European Council are the next milestones on the file.\n\nIn the [**MERICS Insights: Dinner time – Why Merz must pivot Germany away from a piecemeal China policy**](https://public-eur.mkt.dynamics.com/api/orgs/7cdc142b-8d43-40f4-82ad-217169f0e4a0/r/6_QFxHudE02QPGDeEhQAAAAAAAA?msdynmkt_target=%7B%22TargetUrl%22%3A%22https%253A%252F%252Fpublic-eur.mkt.dynamics.com%252Fapi%252Fv1.0%252Forgs%252F7cdc142b-8d43-40f4-82ad-217169f0e4a0%252Fchannels%252Fmails%252Fvib%252Fb92050b0-1847-ec11-8c60-6045bd886b67_552149e5-336b-f111-a826-7c1e52742fd0_7f2b4065-58e8-2852-264a-bfc50064f35c_14ecf5bd-316b-f111-a826-7c1e52742fd0%22%2C%22RedirectOptions%22%3A%7B%225%22%3Anull%2C%221%22%3Anull%7D%7D&msdynmkt_digest=szHKDUsFMGtfl3zEXkWZJQzlSjQHfwH582qzd8gJkj0%3D&msdynmkt_secretVersion=7bb221762d0c46939816d3a5592b1359) (18 June, member-only), I argue that case-by-case dossiers are not enough. Three things matter now for Berlin: supporting a cross-sectoral trade instrument; real supply-chain diversification; and investment in Germany's and the EU's own chokepoints.\n\nNumbers continue to speak one language: the Q1 EU deficit with China was around €95bn, with Séjourné saying it could reach €500bn annually by 2027. Germany accounted for €2bn of the €2.9bn year-on-year widening in the EU's April China balance – two-thirds of the bloc's deterioration. German EV and PHEV imports from China rose 9× to €324m in April; in May, Chinese hybrid exports to the EU were up 184% YoY at US$1.54bn.\n\nMeanwhile in Beijing: The NBS May data showed industrial value-added +4.5% YoY and retail sales down 0.6% YoY – the first decline since December 2022 ([Caixin Jun 16](https://www.caixinglobal.com/2026-06-16/china-retail-sales-shrink-for-first-time-since-2022-in-blow-to-economy-102454580.html), [NBS](https://www.stats.gov.cn/sj/zxfb/202606/t20260616_1963954.html)). PKU-NSD dean **Huang Yiping** writes that supply-side fixes can no longer carry the weak-demand problem ([CF40](https://www.cf40.org.cn/article/1/289307)). Europe is absorbing China's domestic-demand shortfall through the trade account.\n\nAnd in Germany? At least there is a debate. It may not be the smartest path forward for Merz to call for Plaza-Accord-style talks on the yuan ([SCMP Jun 20](https://www.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy/article/3357742/germany-hews-eus-tough-china-line-call-plaza-accord-talks-yuan)), as for China's leaders the way how the US forced Japan to restructure its economy is probably – next to the decline of the Soviet Union – the key historical development to prevent from repeating. The Kiel Institute argues \"broad-based tariffs on products from China should not be the tool of choice\" ([Hinz/Erhardt/Chowdhry](https://www.kielinstitut.de/publications/news/competing-with-china-broad-tariffs-not-the-best-option/)). And Spahn told a CCG-KAS dialogue in Beijing that Germany loses \"10,000 industrial jobs every month\" to overcapacity and subsidies ([CCG transcript](https://www.ccgupdate.org/p/transcript-german-cducsu-delegation)).\n\n**What to watch:** Wang Wentao in Brussels at month's end, as possible von der Leyen toolbox proposal in October, and whether Merz follows the Plaza-Accord rhetoric with more details.",
      "items": [],
